pullRequest.body:
We now have a general treatment of the Hurwitz zeta function. The Riemann zeta is just the Hurwitz zeta for `a = 0`, and this PR reimplements it as such. 

I have tried to carry over the `align` statements from the old treatment wherever possible (many of the intermediate lemmas from the previous iteration don't have direct analogues, but the main results do).

Why is this deprecated? Is there a replacement elsewhere?

This is just a backward-compatibility measure: I renamed some declarations, and there's a convention that when you rename `oldName` to `newName` you add `@[deprecated] alias oldName := newName` so anyone still using `oldName` in their code will get a polite message saying "oldName is deprecated, use newName", rather than everything just stopping working. (Cf. Sebastien's recent post in the PNT+ thread, about the experience of bumping the mathlib version used in the PNT+ repo being less painful than expected owing to the deprecated alias system.)

As for _why_ the declarations were renamed: originally we had `riemannCompletedZeta`, ported from `riemann_completed_zeta` in Mathlib3. On rewriting this stuff, I didn't like the look of `hurwitzCompletedZeta` -- it's a completion of Hurwitz' zeta function, not Hurwitz' completion of a zeta function (while both readings work for Riemann!) so went for `completedHurwitzZeta`, and changed the Riemann zeta for consistency with that.
(PS. Evidently you already know this, since you use the same mechanism in your `AddChar` PR; and I learned from your code there that one does not need to specify the new name in the deprecation.)
My point is that you deprecated the *new* names. This was confusing me.

> My point is that you deprecated the new names. This was confusing me.

No, I don't think I did, unless I'm grotesquely misunderstanding how the deprecation mechanism works. The old definitions were `riemannCompletedXXX`, they have been replaced by `completedRiemanXXX`, and I am adding back `riemannCompletedXXX` as a deprecated alias for the new declaration.
My understanding is that when you write `@[deprecated <name>]`, then this deprecates `<name>` (and `<name>` was `completedRiemann...`.

> My understanding is that when you write `@[deprecated <name>]`, then this deprecates `<name>` (and `<name>` was `completedRiemann...`.

No, the `<name>` is the replacement.
Thanks for clarifying (and sorry for the noise!).

```suggestion
    completedRiemannZeta s =
      (Ï€ : â„‚) ^ (-s / 2) * Gamma (s / 2) * âˆ‘' n : â„•, 1 / (n : â„‚) ^ s := by
```
is easier to parse, I think.
Same question as above: why are these deprecated?
Same answer as above :smile:

```suggestion
  Â· simp only [h, Nat.cast_zero, zero_cpow (Complex.ne_zero_of_one_lt_re hs), div_zero]
  Â· rfl
```
I think this is clearer (and worth the additional line). (And `mul_zero`  was apparently not necessary.)

```suggestion
  have hs' : s â‰  0 := ne_zero_of_one_lt_re hs
```
(We had this before, but I assume the code had been written before the other discussion.)
Since `hs'` is only used once, this could perhaps be inlined (which does not save a line, though, because the `simpa` below then needs two).
... but most of the lemmas in the `simpa` don't need to be explicitly given anyway.

```suggestion
  Â· simpa only [one_div, Nat.cast_zero, zero_cpow <| ne_zero_of_one_lt_re hs, div_zero,
      Nat.cast_add, Nat.cast_one, zero_add]
```
(with `hs'` inlined).
I've left the `simpa` unsqueezed since it's quite quick (whole proof is < 0.3s), and instead removed the listed lemmas that are already simp lemmas.

Variants of this are already present (e.g., [LSeriesSummable_of_bounded_of_one_lt_re](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/NumberTheory/LSeries/Basic.html#LSeriesSummable_of_bounded_of_one_lt_re)), or, perhaps closer, [summable_riemannZetaSummand](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/NumberTheory/EulerProduct/DirichletLSeries.html#summable_riemannZetaSummand)). Still, I don't think the statement is available in this precise form. It might be a consideration to add it next to [Real.summable_one_div_nat_rpow](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Analysis/PSeries.html#Real.summable_one_div_nat_rpow).
Just to be clear: you're suggesting we add something like `Complex.summable_one_div_nat_cpow`?
Yes. (Without the norm, I would think, but anyway, moving between the two is easy.)
Done. I made a new file for it in order to avoid massively increasing the imports of `Analysis.PSeries`.
`hasSum_zeta_nat` is stated in terms of `HasSum`; I wouldn't describe that as "explicitly as a sum".

(This docstring is the same as it was in the previous code, it's just been relocated.) 

My point is that `hasSum_zeta_nat` is *not* formulated in terms of `riemannZeta` (despite the name) but uses the defining Dirichlet series explicitly. If you prefer another formulation please let me know.

Ah, OK. I was reading "explicitly as a sum" as somehow differentiating from the equality and wondering, since in the `HasSum` version, no actual sum appears. Maybe write "... in terms of a sum over `1/n^(2*k)`" or so.

```suggestion
  Â· rw [â† Nat.cast_two, â† Nat.cast_mul, zeta_nat_eq_tsum_of_gt_one (by omega)]
    simp only [ofReal_tsum, ofReal_div, ofReal_pow, ofReal_natCast, ofReal_one]
  Â· norm_cast
```
`norm_num` looks out of scope (no numerical computation), and inequalities of natural numbers or integers can be (efficiently) dealt with using `omega`.
Good point, I think I must have got `norm_num` and `norm_cast` muddled.

```suggestion
    simp only [ofReal_div, ofReal_one, ofReal_pow, ofReal_natCast]
```

